{\colortbl ;\red0\green0\blue0;\red255\green0\blue128;}
{\*\generator Msftedit 5.41.15.1515;}\viewkind4\uc1\pard\cf1\b\f0\fs20 The main idea behind having transactions is that they can be rolled back ... that is, the data not committed ... when you decide that should happen. Magic will automatically roll back a transaction under some circumstances, such as if a database error occurred. \par
\par
But you can also manually roll back a transaction based on any event or data condition, by using the \cf2 Rollback()\cf1  function.\par
\par
This example shows how to rollback changes to a child task, or to the child task and the parent record, using \cf2 Rollback()\cf1 .\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
{\colortbl ;\red0\green0\blue0;\red255\green0\blue128;}
{\*\generator Msftedit 5.41.15.1515;}\viewkind4\uc1\pard\cf1\b\f0\fs20 This task opens a transaction in \cf2 Task Prefix\cf1 , so changes to any phone number are all in the same transaction.\par
\par
When you press the \cf2 Rollback current\cf1  button, the current transaction is rolled back, so all phone number changes disappear.\par
\par
When you press the \cf2 Rollback all\cf1  button, the changes on this screen disappear, and also changes to the parent record.\par
}
